
[1]harness

   H`ARNESS, n.

   1. Armor; the whole accouterments or equipments of a knight or
   horseman; originally perhaps defensive armor, but in a more modern and
   enlarged sense, the furniture of a military man,or offensive, as a
   casque, cuirass,helmet, girdle, sword,buckler, &c.

   2. The furniture of a draught horse, whether for a wagon, coach, gig,
   chaise, &c., called in some of the American states, tackle or tackling,
   with which, in its primary sense, it is synonymous.

     H`ARNESS, v.t. To dress in armor; to equip with armor for war, as a
                                  horseman.

   Harnessed in rugged steel.

   1. To put on the furniture of a horse for draught.

   Harness the horses. Jer.46.

   2. To defend; to equip or furnish for defense. 1 Macc.4.
